  <mads:note type="source">His Praecepta [CF] 1991: PHI CD ROM #5.3, Latin Canon, bibliographic screen (Cn. Marcius vates)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Pauly-Wissowa: 28. Halbbd., col. 1538, 1541-1542; "Marcius", #2 (Marcius; Marcius vates; under the name Marcius a collection of praecepta from 2 cent. B.C., 
but it is difficult to decide whether there is any connection with vates Marcius)</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Oxford class. dict., 1st ed.: p. 537 (Marcius; eponymous author of a number of miscellaneous 
oracular sayings current in Rome in early days. According to Cicero, there were Marcii frates, men of noble birth who wrote prophecies; 
according to Livy, there was only one, vates Marcius. Of an ancient collection of praecepta under the name Marcius three
Saturnian quotations survive; connection with Marcius vates uncertain)</mads:note>
